8, "end": 2312}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1280"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "collagen", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9874573349952698, "span": {"begin": 2322, "end": 2330}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005355"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "fibrotic lesions", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999910593032837, "span": {"begin": 2348, "end": 2364}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9665261507034302, "span": {"begin": 2368, "end": 2372}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9829244017601013, "span": {"begin": 2404, "end": 2408}}, {"id": ["mim:263400", "mesh:C563918"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "deficient in Nuclear factor erythroid 2-related factor 2", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999001026153564, "span": {"begin": 2409, "end": 2465}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4780"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Nuclear factor erythroid 2-related factor 2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.886031985282898, "span": {"begin": 2422, "end": 2465}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4780"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Nrf2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9983118772506714, "span": {"begin": 2467, "end": 2471}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002244"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "carbon", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9702073931694031, "span": {"begin": 2506, "end": 2512}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9438369870185852, "span": {"begin": 2683, "end": 2687}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4780"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Nrf2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9965040683746338, "span": {"begin": 2696, "end": 2700}}], "text": "The biological plausibility of this KER is high. There is a mechanistic relationship between an increase in pro-inflammatory cells and mediators, and damage to the ACM (Bhalla et al., 2009; Ward, 2003; Zemans et al., 2009).  Exposure to high doses of insoluble nanomaterials can impair the macrophage-mediated clearance process, initiating chronicity of inflammation characterized by cytokine release, reactive oxygen species (ROS) synthesis and the tissue damage cascade (Palecanda and Kobzik, 2001) and subsequently leading to tissue injury. For example, exposure to crystalline silica generates oxidative stress, increased release of pro-inflammatory cytokines (e.g. Tumor necrosis factor alpha [TNF-&alpha;], Interleukin [IL]-1, IL-6), activation of transcription factors (e.g. Nuclear factor kappa B [NF-&kappa;B], Activator protein [AP-1]), and other cell signalling pathways including Mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs)&nbsp;and Extracellular signal-regulated kinases [ERKs] (Fubini and Hubbard 2003; Hubbard et al., 2001; Hubbard et al., 2002). In silicosis, TNF-&alpha; is suggested to play a critical role in the observed pathogenicity (Castranova et al., 2004), which in turn, is dependent on activation of NF-&kappa;B and ROS synthesis (Cassel et al.,2008; Kawasaki et al., 2015; Shi et al.,1998). It has been proposed that IPF is a disorder of elevated oxidative stress, with the existence of an oxidant-antioxidant imbalance in distal alveolar air spaces (MacNee, 2001). Several studies have reported that antioxidant treatment attenuates the bleomycin-induced oxidative burden and subsequent pulmonary fibrosis (Punithavathi, et al., 2000;&nbsp;Serrano-Mollar et al., 2003; Wang et al., 2002).  Mice deficient in NLR family pyrin domain containing 3 (Nalp3) showed reduced inflammation, lower cytokine production and dampened fibrotic response following exposure to asbestos or silica (Dostert et al., 2008). Single-walled carbon nanotube exposure induces alveolar macrophage activation, enhanced oxidative stress, increased and persistent expression of pro-inflammatory mediators associated with chronic inflammation and severe granuloma formation in mice (Chou et al., 2008). Bleomycin treatment induces increased lung weight, epithelial cell death, inflammation, increased hydroxyproline content, collagen accumulation and fibrotic lesions in mice, all of which were elevated in mice deficient in Nuclear factor erythroid 2-related factor 2 (Nrf2) (Cho et al., 2004). Multi-walled carbon nanotube (MWCNT)-induced fibrotic response is the result of interplay between oxidative stress and inflammation, which determines the severity of the fibrotic pathology. Mice lacking Nrf2 that is associated with mounting antioxidant defense against oxidative stress, exhibit exuberant fibrotic responses to MWCNT (Dong and Ma, 2016).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:57:45 +0000 2026"}